  "title": "The Ring of '-ING'",
  "learningGoal": "The learner will master the soft nasal release of the '-ing' suffix /ɪŋ/, avoiding hard 'g' consonant closures (/ɪŋg/) often produced by native Hindi speakers.",
  "difficultyLevel": "beginner",
  "baseLanguage": "hi",
  "targetLanguage": "en",
  "estimatedTime": 45,
  "prerequisites": ["en_hi_M2B2_lesson_001"],
  "instructions": "In English, the '-ing' sound is nasal. It happens in the back of your nose. DO NOT say a hard 'G' at the end. It is not 'Cook-inGuh!'. It is a soft 'Cook-ing'. Listen carefully to the audio and repeat these 15 action phrases.",
  "contentItems": [
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "Try to let the sound fade out smoothly in your throat instead of clicking your tongue hard for a G."
    }
  ],
